am01='''{{flagIOC2athlete|Almas Kassenov|KAZ|2005 Asian Indoor Games}}'''\n| RD3-score01='''59'''\n| RD3-team02={{flagIOC2athlete|Vahid Roshani|IRI|2005 Asian Indoor Games}}\n| RD3-score02=58\n}}\n\n====79 kg====\n{{4TeamBracket-Compact-NoSeeds-Byes\n|RD1=Semifinals\n|RD2=Final<br />18 November\n\n| team-width=185\n| score-width=40\n\n| RD1-team03={{flagIOC2athlete| |IND|2005 Asian Indoor Games}}\n| RD1-score03=&nbsp;\n| RD1-team04='''{{flagIOC2athlete|Riadh Mohammed|IRQ|2005 Asian Indoor Games}}'''\n| RD1-score04='''RSCO'''\n\n| RD2-team01='''{{flagIOC2athlete|Jad Al-Wahash|JOR|2005 Asian Indoor Games}}'''\n| RD2-score01='''RSCO'''\n| RD2-team02={{flagIOC2athlete|Riadh Mohammed|IRQ|2005 Asian Indoor Games}}\n| RD2-score02=&nbsp;\n}}\n\n====86 kg====\n{{4TeamBracket-Compact-NoSeeds-Byes\n|RD1=Semifinals\n|RD2=Final<br />18 November\n\n| team-width=185\n| score-width=40\n\n| RD1-team03={{flagIOC2athlete|Mohammed Kadhim|IRQ|2005 Asian Indoor Games}}\n| RD1-score03=57\n| RD1-team04='''{{flagIOC2athlete|Abdolvahab Maroufi|IRI|2005 Asian Indoor Games}}'''\n| RD1-score04='''60'''\n\n| RD2-team01={{flagIOC2athlete|Ali Al-Tamari|JOR|2005 Asian Indoor Games}}\n| RD2-score01=57\n| RD2-team02='''{{flagIOC2athlete|Abdolvahab Maroufi|IRI|2005 Asian Indoor Games}}'''\n| RD2-score02='''60'''\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050714235923/http://www.baigoc2005.com/ 2005 Asian Indoor Games official website] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120220040827/http://muay.wmf-j.org/article/613906.html Muay Japan] \n\n{{Events at the 2005 Asian Indoor Games}}\n{{Asian Indoor Games Muay Thai}}\n\n[[Category:2005 Asian Indoor Games events]]\n[[Category:Muaythai at the Asian Indoor Games|2005]]\n[[Category:2005 in muay Thai|Indoor Games]]\n[[Category:Muay Thai competitions in Thailand|Indoor Games]]\n", "name_user": "Mohsen1248", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muaythai_at_the_2005_Asian_Indoor_Games"}
{"title_page": "Aberbargoed", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                     = Wales\n|welsh_name                  = Aberbargod\n|coordinates                 = {{coord|51.6968|-3.2240|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name               = Aberbargoed\n|unitary_wales               = [[Caerphilly (county borough)|Caerphilly]]\n|constituency_westminster    = [[Caerphilly (UK Parliament constituency)|Caerphilly]]\n|constituency_welsh_assembly = [[Caerphilly (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Caerphilly]]|post_town                   = CAERPHILLY\n|postcode_district           = CF81\n|postcode_area               = CF\n|dial_code                   = 01443\n|os_grid_reference           = SO155005\n|population                  = 9,184 \n}}\n'''Aberbargoed''' ({{lang-cy|Aberbargod}}) is a small [[town]] in the [[Wales|Welsh]] [[county borough]] of [[Caerphilly (county borough)|Caerphilly]], within the [[Historic counties of Wales|historic boundaries]] of [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]], [[South Wales|south]] [[Wales]]. Aberbargoed once contained the largest ever colliery [[waste tip]] in Europe,<ref name=\"Caerphilly.gov.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.caerphilly.gov.uk/bargoedtowncouncil/local_history.html|title=the largest ever man made colliery waste tip in Europe|date=February 9, 2011|publisher= www.caerphilly.gov.uk|accessdate=9 February 2011}}</ref> although this has now been reclaimed and turned into a [[country park]].\n\n== Mining ==\n[[Coal mining]] operations in Bargoed Colliery started in 1897 when the [[Powell Duffryn]] Steam Coal Company started to sink the shaft. In 1901, the \"Ras Las\" nine-foot seam was discovered at a depth of 625 yards. The north and south shafts were completed. In November 1903, Sir Alfred Thomas, M.P. for East Glamorgan, started the engines to raise the first four trams of coal.<br />\nBy 1910, the pit was employing 1,943 miners and was the largest coal mine in the [[Rhymney Valley]]. On 10 December 1908, it broke the world record for production when a ten-hour shift produced 3,562 [[ton]]s of [[coal]]. It further broke its own record on 23 April 1909 when 4,020 tons were raised in a ten-hour shift.<br />Bargoed Colliery closed on 4 June 1977. By this time, only 360 men were employed there. There is a legend that has it, The Flame lived in Aberbargoed for 27 years before moving to Penpedairheol\n\n== Population ==\nThe population of Pont Aberbargoed was 351 in the [[census]] of 1851. Aberbargoed reached a peak in 1961 of 5,157, and had dropped to 3,882 according to the 1991 Census. Bargoed in 1921 had a population of 2, dropping to 1 by 1991.<ref name=\"Welshicons.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.welshicons.org.uk/html/aberbargoed.php |title=Population figures from 1991 census |date=February 8, 2011 |publisher=www.welshicons.org |accessdate=8 February 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101173342/http://welshicons.org.uk/html/aberbargoed.php |archivedate=1 January 2011 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n== Modern Day ==\nThe coal-mining waste tip that lay between Bargoed and Aberbargoed once towered to a height of 400 feet in the 1970s. The local school had a [[Plant a tree in '73]] campaign in an attempt to make it more pleasurable on the eye. The tip has now been levelled and the area has been reclaimed with walkways. The colliery has gone and is now home to an Ambulance Station and other small industries.<br />There are also developments with a new retail outlet in the area where the tip once stood.\n\nThe large tip at [[Bedwellty]] is still there, but has been grassed over and now looks much like the surrounding countryside.<br /> Aberbargoed now has an extensive area of grasslands that are protected due to the finding of a rare [[butterfly]]: the [[Marsh fritillary]] ''Euphydryas aurinia'' has been found in the [[marsh]]y area north of where Bedwellty School once stood.  Recently a bypass has been built through the park allowing road users to bypass the town of [[Bargoed]].\n\n<!--  Commented out: [[Image:Aberbargoed1.jpg|thumb|right|The Old Mill Pub, circa 1900. Copyright Paul James, ''The History of Bargoed, Gilfach, and Aberbargoed''. Published by ''Old Bakehouse Publications''. Permission granted for reproduction with correct citation only.]] -->\n\n== Notable people ==\n:''{{main|:Category:People from Aberbargoed}}''\n* [[Harold Finch|Sir Harold Josiah Finch]] (politician)\n* The jazz pianist and composer [[Geoff Eales]] was born in Aberbargoed.\n* [[Luke Evans]] (actor)\n* Listed on the War Memorial in the middle of the village is the name of [[Glyndwr Michael]]. His body, given the fictional name of \"Major Martin\", was used in \"[[Operation Mincemeat]]\", a deception operation by British Intelligence during [[World War II]].\n*[[Darren Smith]] famous moron.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{cite book |last=James |first=Paul |title=The History of Bargoed, Gilfach and Aberbargoed in Photographs, Vol. 3 |year=2002 |publisher=Old Bakehouse Publications |isbn=1-874538-64-6 }}<br />  {{cite book |last=Gelligaer Historical Society |title=Gelligaer |year=1972 |publisher=Gelligaer Historical Society}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.caerphilly.gov.uk/thecouncil/democracy/councillors/aberbargoed.htm Aberbargoed Electoral Ward Web Page]\n*[http://www.wales.nhs.uk/sites3/page.cfm?orgid=79&pid=979 NHS Wales's Aberbargoed Hospital Web Page]\n*[http://www.jncc.gov.uk/protectedsites/sacselection/SAC.asp?EUCode=UK0030071 Web Page of Aberbargoed Grasslands Conservation Area]\n*[http://www.welshcoalmines.co.uk Welsh Coal Mines - all the pits, all the histories]\n\n{{Caerphilly}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Caerphilly County Borough]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                     = Wales\n|welsh_name                  = Aberbargod\n|coordinates                 = {{coord|51.6968|-3.2240|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name               = Aberbargoed\n|unitary_wales               = [[Caerphilly (county borough)|Caerphilly]]\n|constituency_westminster    = [[Caerphilly (UK Parliament constituency)|Caerphilly]]\n|constituency_welsh_assembly = [[Caerphilly (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Caerphilly]]|post_town                   = CAERPHILLY\n|postcode_district           = CF81\n|postcode_area               = CF\n|dial_code                   = 01443\n|os_grid_reference           = SO155005\n|population                  = 9,184 \n}}\n'''Aberbargoed''' ({{lang-cy|Aberbargod}}) is a small [[town]] in the [[Wales|Welsh]] [[county borough]] of [[Caerphilly (county borough)|Caerphilly]], within the [[Historic counties of Wales|historic boundaries]] of [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]], [[South Wales|south]] [[Wales]]. Aberbargoed once contained the largest ever colliery [[waste tip]] in Europe,<ref name=\"Caerphilly.gov.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.caerphilly.gov.uk/bargoedtowncouncil/local_history.html|title=the largest ever man made colliery waste tip in Europe|date=February 9, 2011|publisher= www.caerphilly.gov.uk|accessdate=9 February 2011}}</ref> although this has now been reclaimed and turned into a [[country park]].\n\n== Mining ==\n[[Coal mining]] operations in Bargoed Colliery started in 1897 when the [[Powell Duffryn]] Steam Coal Company started to sink the shaft. In 1901, the \"Ras Las\" nine-foot seam was discovered at a depth of 625 yards. The north and south shafts were completed. In November 1903, Sir Alfred Thomas, M.P. for East Glamorgan, started the engines to raise the first four trams of coal.<br />\nBy 1910, the pit was employing 1,943 miners and was the largest coal mine in the [[Rhymney Valley]]. On 10 December 1908, it broke the world record for production when a ten-hour shift produced 3,562 [[ton]]s of [[coal]]. It further broke its own record on 23 April 1909 when 4,020 tons were raised in a ten-hour shift.<br />Bargoed Colliery closed on 4 June 1977. By this time, only 360 men were employed there. There is a legend that has it, The Flame lived in Aberbargoed for 27 years before moving to Penpedairheol\n\n== Population ==\nThe population of Pont Aberbargoed was 351 in the [[census]] of 1851. Aberbargoed reached a peak in 1961 of 5,157, and had dropped to 3,882 according to the 1991 Census. Bargoed in 1921 had a population of 2, dropping to 1 by 1991.<ref name=\"Welshicons.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.welshicons.org.uk/html/aberbargoed.php |title=Population figures from 1991 census |date=February 8, 2011 |publisher=www.welshicons.org |accessdate=8 February 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101173342/http://welshicons.org.uk/html/aberbargoed.php |archivedate=1 January 2011 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n== Modern Day ==\nThe coal-mining waste tip that lay between Bargoed and Aberbargoed once towered to a height of 400 feet in the 1970s. The local school had a [[Plant a tree in '73]] campaign in an attempt to make it more pleasurable on the eye. The tip has now been levelled and the area has been reclaimed with walkways. The colliery has gone and is now home to an Ambulance Station and other small industries.<br />There are also developments with a new retail outlet in the area where the tip once stood.\n\nThe large tip at [[Bedwellty]] is still there, but has been grassed over and now looks much like the surrounding countryside.<br /> Aberbargoed now has an extensive area of grasslands that are protected due to the finding of a rare [[butterfly]]: the [[Marsh fritillary]] ''Euphydryas aurinia'' has been found in the [[marsh]]y area north of where Bedwellty School once stood.  Recently a bypass has been built through the park allowing road users to bypass the town of [[Bargoed]].\n\n<!--  Commented out: [[Image:Aberbargoed1.jpg|thumb|right|The Old Mill Pub, circa 1900. Copyright Paul James, ''The History of Bargoed, Gilfach, and Aberbargoed''. Published by ''Old Bakehouse Publications''. Permission granted for reproduction with correct citation only.]] -->\n\n== Notable people ==\n:''{{main|:Category:People from Aberbargoed}}''\n* [[Harold Finch|Sir Harold Josiah Finch]] (politician)\n* The jazz pianist and composer [[Geoff Eales]] was born in Aberbargoed.\n* [[Luke Evans]] (actor)\n* Listed on the War Memorial in the middle of the village is the name of [[Glyndwr Michael]]. His body, given the fictional name of \"Major Martin\", was used in \"[[Operation Mincemeat]]\", a deception operation by British Intelligence during [[World War II]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{cite book |last=James |first=Paul |title=The History of Bargoed, Gilfach and Aberbargoed in Photographs, Vol. 3 |year=2002 |publisher=Old Bakehouse Publications |isbn=1-874538-64-6 }}<br />  {{cite book |last=Gelligaer Historical Society |title=Gelligaer |year=1972 |publisher=Gelligaer Historical Society}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.caerphilly.gov.uk/thecouncil/democracy/councillors/aberbargoed.htm Aberbargoed Electoral Ward Web Page]\n*[http://www.wales.nhs.uk/sites3/page.cfm?orgid=79&pid=979 NHS Wales's Aberbargoed Hospital Web Page]\n*[http://www.jncc.gov.uk/protectedsites/sacselection/SAC.asp?EUCode=UK0030071 Web Page of Aberbargoed Grasslands Conservation Area]\n*[http://www.welshcoalmines.co.uk Welsh Coal Mines - all the pits, all the histories]\n\n{{Caerphilly}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Caerphilly County Borough]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:1c60:3600:b92a:5312:f648:43f7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotable people)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aberbargoed"}
